text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild]]%0a%0a!Asian Accent Discrimination%0a%0a:Author: AlexanderW%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aAsian Accent Discrimination%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0ahttps://repository.upenn.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1299&context=pwpl%0a%0aDue to many anti-Asian sentiments still harbored in the US today - especially due to Covid-induced racism, Asian accents are sometimes looked down upon, teased, and even discriminated against. As the study above states, this leads to stigma and decreased opportunities and chances with people with Asian accents.%0a%0ahttp://confidencelearningservices.com/english-chinese-mispronounce/%0a%0aOne word that I can relate to in the above link is the "sheep"/"ship" distinction. In Mandarin Chinese, there is only a tense [i], and no relaxed "i" sound as in "ship". Therefore, I would classify the criticism in the main vowel pronunciation, where the tongue is tensed for both words - making them sound the same. This is common in the Mandarin Chinese accent, as well as in some other Chinese dialects.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210430-230132-465530#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!A similar example in the Colombian accent %0a-> - sanjana_m%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aNot being able to distinguish between vowels is an issue that is common in many accents. The sheep example reminds me of a similar confusion with the Colombian accent in the show Modern Family. One of the main characters, Gloria, has a thick Colombian accent, which is often used for comedic purposes. Another character's name is Luke, and in one scene, she is telling "Luke" to "look." However, with her accent, the vowels sounded the same, and it caused a lot of confusion for Luke. %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210430-230132-465530#%0a#foxbegin 210509-021523-91760#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Decreased work opportunities on the basis of accents %0a-> - ruiranx%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aTo elaborate on the point of decreased opportunities, there was some research [1] conducted on the effect of Chinese accent strength on perceived employability. The findings, disappointingly but not surprisingly, were that applicants with stronger accents were perceived as less competent, likeable, and employable.%0a%0aAccent discrimination in employment is definitely a whole can of worms, and I've definitely found myself grateful at times that I don't have a Chinese accent. Interestingly enough, I've received a non-negligible amount of comments during interview feedback that I'm "articulate" or "well-spoken", and I wonder how much of that is because the interviewers expect me to have an accent since my name is noticeably Chinese.%0a%0a[1] https://journals.aom.org/doi/abs/10.5465/ambpp.2016.14315abstract%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210509-021523-91760#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a#foxbegin 210501-064051-28320#%0a(:div1 class=messagehead:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a[-30.04.2021 - 23:40-] &nbsp; %0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c%0a{[foxdelrange button 210501-064051-28320 {$FullName} ]}%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1end:)%0a!!!!!Abi_S%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0a'''Asian accent'''%0a>>messageitem%3c%3c%0aspecific to covid, having an Asian accent, the stereotype now includes person responsible/played