diff:1620526523:1619851250:=60,72d59%0a%3c #foxbegin 210509-021523-91760#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Decreased work opportunities on the basis of accents %0a%3c -> - ruiranx%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c To elaborate on the point of decreased opportunities, there was some research [1] conducted on the effect of Chinese accent strength on perceived employability. The findings, disappointingly but not surprisingly, were that applicants with stronger accents were perceived as less competent, likeable, and employable.%0a%3c %0a%3c Accent discrimination in employment is definitely a whole can of worms, and I've definitely found myself grateful at times that I don't have a Chinese accent. Interestingly enough, I've received a non-negligible amount of comments during interview feedback that I'm "articulate" or "well-spoken", and I wonder how much of that is because the interviewers expect me to have an accent since my name is noticeably Chinese.%0a%3c %0a%3c [1] https://journals.aom.org/doi/abs/10.5465/ambpp.2016.14315abstract%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210509-021523-91760#%0a
